# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cysteine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The stereoisomer (*S*)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (also referred to as L-P5C) is an intermediate metabolite in the biosynthesis and degradation of proline and arginine.
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In prokaryotic proline biosynthesis, GSA is synthesized from γ-glutamyl phosphate by the enzyme γ-glutamyl phosphate reductase.
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In most eukaryotes, GSA is synthesised from the amino acid glutamate by the bifunctional enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthase (P5CS).
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The human P5CS is encoded by the *ALDH18A1* gene.
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase converts L-P5C into proline.
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In proline degradation, the enzyme proline dehydrogenase produces P5C from proline, and the enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase converts GSA to glutamate.
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In many prokaryotes, proline dehydrogenase and P5C dehydrogenase form a bifunctional enzyme that prevents the release of P5C during proline degradation.
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] A reciprocal regulation of delta 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthetase (P5CS) and proline dehydrogenase genes controls proline levels during and after osmotic stress in plants proportional to the level of proline.
[src:cysteine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] This allows an optimum level of proline to be produced from reduced nitrogen to control osmotic stress.
[src:cysteine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme 3-hydroxyanthranilate 3,4-dioxygenase uses oxygen to cleave the aromatic ring of 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid, giving 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde.
[src:cysteine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The kynurenine pathway of tryptophan catabolism leads to nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide and supplies the nicotinic acid component of that cofactor.
[src:cysteine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] Alternatively, 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde can be acted on by the enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase to give 2-aminomuconic semialdehyde, an unstable open-chain precursor of picolinic acid.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] 2-Aminomuconic acid is a six-carbon molecule bearing two carboxyl groups, two conjugated double bonds, and a primary amino substituent at carbon 2.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] The molecule is commonly encountered in its ionized form, 2-aminomuconate, under physiological and environmental aqueous conditions.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Specific physical constants such as pKa values, solubility, and spectroscopic data are not comprehensively tabulated in the primary literature and should be added only with a verified source.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In microbial biodegradation of aromatic xenobiotics, for example certain nitroaromatic compounds, where ring-cleavage pathways produce aminomuconic intermediates prior to further downstream processing.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] The compound appears as a catabolic intermediate in several bacterial strains studied under laboratory conditions.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In the oxidative degradation of tryptophan via the kynurenine pathway, intermediates with structural relation to aminomuconate are formed during enzymatic ring opening and aldehyde oxidation steps.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Wherever it appears, the ionized form 2-aminomuconate is typically the biologically relevant species.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Details such as kinetic constants, mechanism and gene names vary by organism and strain and should be cited from the primary enzymology literature for each specific claim.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In environmental microbiology, pathways involving 2-aminomuconate are part of bacterial systems that allow mineralization of aromatic pollutants, converting recalcitrant compounds into metabolites that join central carbon metabolism.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Such pathways are of interest for biodegradation and bioremediation research.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] 2-Aminomuconic semialdehyde is an intermediate in the kynurenine pathway of tryptophan metabolism, which leads to picolinic acid or quinolinic acid.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase produces it from 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde, a compound which would form quinolinic acid in the absence of that enzyme.
[src:cysteine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] 2-Aminomuconic semialdehyde itself is chemically unstable and spontaneously ring-closes to picolinic acid, with loss of water.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:cysteine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:cysteine/4-dimethylaminophenol] Heating dimethylaniline N-oxide in concentrated sulfuric acid causes a Bamberger rearrangement to 2- and 4-dimethylaminophenols.
[src:cysteine/4-dimethylaminophenol] 4-Dimethylaminophenol has been used as an antidote for cyanide poisoning.
[src:cysteine/4-dimethylaminophenol] It has also been shown to be effective in treating hydrogen sulfide toxicity.
[src:cysteine/4-dimethylaminophenol] This is suitable as an emergency treatment only; treatment must be followed up with sodium thiosulfate or cobalamin.
[src:cysteine/4-dimethylaminophenol] In an animal model, it has shown effectiveness when given intramuscularly.
[src:cysteine/4-dimethylaminophenol] Though, intramuscular injection should be avoid due to the probability of muscular necrosis after injection.
[src:cysteine/4-dimethylaminophenol] Intravenous injection is recommended in a dose of 250 mg.
[src:cysteine/4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic-acid] It is an intermediary compound in the biosynthesis of scytonemin.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The thiol is susceptible to oxidation to give the disulfide derivative cystine, which serves an important structural role in many proteins.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In this case, the symbol **Cyx** is sometimes used.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The deprotonated form can generally be described by the symbol **Cym** as well.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] When used as a food additive, cysteine has the E number E920.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine is encoded by the codons UGU and UGC.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Like other amino acids (not as a residue of a protein), cysteine exists as a zwitterion.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine has l chirality in the older d/l notation based on homology to d- and l-glyceraldehyde.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In the newer *R*/*S* system of designating chirality, based on the atomic numbers of atoms near the asymmetric carbon, cysteine (and selenocysteine) have *R* chirality, because of the presence of sulfur (or selenium) as a second neighbor to the asymmetric carbon atom.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The remaining chiral amino acids, having lighter atoms in that position, have *S* chirality.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Replacing sulfur with selenium gives selenocysteine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Some foods considered rich in cysteine include poultry, eggs, beef, and whole grains.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In high-protein diets, cysteine may be partially responsible for reduced blood pressure and stroke risk.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Although classified as a nonessential amino acid, in rare cases, cysteine may be essential for infants, the elderly, and individuals with certain metabolic diseases or who suffer from malabsorption syndromes.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine can usually be synthesized by the human body under normal physiological conditions if a sufficient quantity of methionine is available through the transsulfuration pathway.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The majority of l-cysteine is obtained industrially by hydrolysis of animal materials, such as poultry feathers or hog hair.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Despite widespread rumor, human hair is rarely a source material.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Indeed, food additive or cosmetic product manufactures may not legally source from human hair in the European Union.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Some animal-originating sources of l-cysteine as a food additive contravene kosher, halal, vegan, or vegetarian diets.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] To avoid this problem, synthetic l-cysteine, compliant with Jewish kosher and Muslim halal laws, is also available, albeit at a higher price.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The typical synthetic route involves fermentation with an artificial *E. coli* strain.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Alternatively, Evonik (formerly Degussa) introduced a route from substituted thiazolines.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] *Pseudomonas thiazolinophilum* hydrolyzes racemic 2‑amino-Δ2‑thiazoline-4‑carboxylic acid to l‑cysteine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In animals, biosynthesis begins with the amino acid serine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The sulfur is derived from methionine, which is converted to homocysteine through the intermediate *S*-adenosylmethionine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cystathionine beta-synthase then combines homocysteine and serine to form the asymmetrical thioether cystathionine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The enzyme cystathionine gamma-lyase converts the cystathionine into cysteine and alpha-ketobutyrate.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] This pathway is called the transsulfuration pathway.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In plants and bacteria, cysteine biosynthesis also starts from serine, which is converted to *O*-acetylserine by the enzyme serine transacetylase.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The enzyme cysteine synthase, using sulfide sources, converts this ester into cysteine, releasing acetate.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The cysteine thiol group is nucleophilic and easily oxidized.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The reactivity is enhanced when the thiol is ionized, and cysteine residues in proteins have pKa values close to neutrality, so are often in their reactive thiolate form in the cell.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Because of its high reactivity, the thiol group of cysteine has numerous biological functions.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The thiol group in proteins can usually be oxidized in the following ways, where GSH is glutathione, GSSG is glutathione disulfide, RSH is a protein containing a thiol group with R being the protein residue.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Disulfide formation stabilizes protein folded structure.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Reduction of disulfinide protein can be done by thioredoxin or thioredoxin reductase.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] It common in secreted and membrane proteins that require a certain mechanical property to function, such as keratin.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] It is used for protein regulation, such as in the ferredoxin-thioredoxin system.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Glutathionylation is common in the cytosol and mitochondria.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] It can protect the reactive thiol, and it also can perform post-translational regulation of the protein.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Reduction of glutathionylated protein can be done by GSH or glutaredoxin.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Sulfenylation is common in redox signalling.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Sulfinylation is further oxidation, also common in redox signalling.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Sulfonylation is an irreversible oxidation.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] It is often associated with the sulfonylation or sulfoconjugation of steroidal hormones.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Due to the ability of thiols to undergo redox reactions, cysteine and cysteinyl residues have antioxidant properties.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Its antioxidant properties are typically expressed in the tripeptide glutathione, which occurs in humans and other organisms.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The systemic availability of oral glutathione (GSH) is negligible; so it must be biosynthesized from its constituent amino acids, cysteine, glycine, and glutamic acid.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] While glutamic acid is usually sufficient because amino acid nitrogen is recycled through glutamate as an intermediary, dietary cysteine and glycine supplementation can improve synthesis of glutathione.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine is an important source of sulfide in human metabolism.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The sulfide in iron-sulfur clusters and in nitrogenase is extracted from cysteine, which is converted to alanine in the process.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Beyond the iron-sulfur proteins, many other metal cofactors in enzymes are bound to the thiolate substituent of cysteinyl residues.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Examples include zinc in zinc fingers and alcohol dehydrogenase, copper in the blue copper proteins, iron in cytochrome P450, and nickel in the [NiFe]-hydrogenases.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The thiol group also has a high affinity for heavy metals, so that proteins containing cysteine, such as metallothionein, will bind metals such as mercury, lead, and cadmium tightly.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Silver ions can also bind tightly to cysteine and cause secondary structure changes in cysteine-containing peptides, e.g. leading to alpha helix formation.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] This is also the case for zinc fingers in which silver ions can replace zinc and form stable zinc/cysteine clusters with partial alpha helical structure.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The extent of alpha helix formation increases with the number of cysteines.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In the translation of messenger RNA molecules to produce polypeptides, cysteine is coded for by the UGU and UGC codons.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine has traditionally been considered to be a hydrophilic amino acid, based largely on the chemical parallel between its thiol group and the hydroxyl groups in the side chains of other polar amino acids.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] However, the cysteine side chain has been shown to stabilize hydrophobic interactions in micelles to a greater degree than the side chain in the nonpolar amino acid glycine and the polar amino acid serine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In a statistical analysis of the frequency with which amino acids appear in various proteins, cysteine residues were found to associate with hydrophobic regions of proteins.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Their hydrophobic tendency was equivalent to that of known nonpolar amino acids such as methionine and tyrosine (tyrosine is polar aromatic but also hydrophobic), those of which were much greater than that of known polar amino acids such as serine and threonine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Hydrophobicity scales, which rank amino acids from most hydrophobic to most hydrophilic, consistently place cysteine towards the hydrophobic end of the spectrum, even when they are based on methods that are not influenced by the tendency of cysteines to form disulfide bonds in proteins.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Therefore, cysteine is now often grouped among the hydrophobic amino acids, though it is sometimes also classified as slightly polar, or polar.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Most cysteine residues are covalently bonded to other cysteine residues to form disulfide bonds, which play an important role in the folding and stability of some proteins, usually proteins secreted to the extracellular medium.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Since most cellular compartments are reducing environments, disulfide bonds are generally unstable in the cytosol with some exceptions as noted below.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Disulfide bonds in proteins are formed by oxidation of the thiol group of cysteine residues.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The other sulfur-containing amino acid, methionine, cannot form disulfide bonds.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] More aggressive oxidants convert cysteine to the corresponding sulfinic acid and sulfonic acid.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine residues play a valuable role by crosslinking proteins, which increases the rigidity of proteins and also functions to confer proteolytic resistance (since protein export is a costly process, minimizing its necessity is advantageous).
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Inside the cell, disulfide bridges between cysteine residues within a polypeptide support the protein's tertiary structure.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Insulin is an example of a protein with cystine crosslinking, wherein two separate peptide chains are connected by a pair of disulfide bonds.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Protein disulfide isomerases catalyze the proper formation of disulfide bonds; the cell transfers dehydroascorbic acid to the endoplasmic reticulum, which oxidizes the environment.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In this environment, cysteines are, in general, oxidized to cystine and are no longer functional as a nucleophiles.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Aside from its oxidation to cystine, cysteine participates in numerous post-translational modifications.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The nucleophilic thiol group allows cysteine to conjugate to other groups, e.g., in prenylation.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Ubiquitin ligases transfer ubiquitin to its pendant, proteins, and caspases, which engage in proteolysis in the apoptotic cycle.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Inteins often function with the help of a catalytic cysteine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] These roles are typically limited to the intracellular milieu, where the environment is reducing, and cysteine is not oxidized to cystine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine is considered a "newcomer" amino acid, being the 17th amino acid incorporated into the genetic code.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Similar to other later-added amino acids such as methionine, tyrosine, and tryptophan, cysteine exhibits strong nucleophilic and redox-active properties.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The primary response of a protein to ROS is the oxidation of cysteine and the loss of free thiol groups, resulting in increased thiyl radicals and associated protein cross-linking.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In contrast, another sulfur-containing, redox-active amino acid, methionine, does not exhibit these biochemical properties and its content is relatively upregulated in mitochondrially encoded proteins.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine, mainly the l-enantiomer, is a precursor in the food, pharmaceutical, and personal-care industries.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] One of the largest applications is the production of flavors.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] For example, the reaction of cysteine with sugars in a Maillard reaction yields meat flavors. l-Cysteine is also used as a processing aid for baking.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In the field of personal care, cysteine is used for permanent-wave applications, predominantly in Asia.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Again, the cysteine is used for breaking up the disulfide bonds in the hair's keratin.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine is a very popular target for site-directed labeling experiments to investigate biomolecular structure and dynamics.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Maleimides selectively attach to cysteine using a covalent Michael addition.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Site-directed spin labeling for EPR or paramagnetic relaxation-enhanced NMR also uses cysteine extensively.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine has been proposed as a preventive or antidote for some of the negative effects of alcohol, including liver damage and hangover.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] It counteracts the poisonous effects of acetaldehyde.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] It binds to acetaldehyde to form the low-toxicity heterocycle methylthioproline.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In a rat study, test animals received an LD90 dose of acetaldehyde.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Those that received cysteine had an 80% survival rate; when both cysteine and thiamine were administered, all animals survived.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The control group had a 10% survival rate.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In 2020 an article was published that suggests L-cysteine might also work in humans.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] D-ribose-L-cysteine (*riboceine*) is a chemical compound developed as a cysteine prodrug intended to increase endogenous production of glutathione, a naturally occurring intracellular antioxidant.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Structurally, it consists of D-ribose, a pentose sugar involved in cellular energy metabolism, chemically bound to L-cysteine, an amino acid required for glutathione biosynthesis.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine is required by sheep to produce wool.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] It is an essential amino acid that is taken in from their feed.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] As a consequence, during drought conditions, sheep produce less wool; however, transgenic sheep that can make their own cysteine have been developed.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Being multifunctional, cysteine undergoes a variety of reactions.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Much attention has focused on protecting the thiol group.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Methylation of cysteine gives S-methylcysteine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Treatment with formaldehyde gives the thiazolidine thioproline.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] With phosgene and related carbonylating agents, cysteine gives procysteine.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Cysteine forms a variety of coordination complexes upon treatment with metal ions.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] This coordination behavior is seen in many metal-cysteine metalloenzymes.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] Relative to most other amino acids, cysteine is much more toxic.
[src:cysteine/cysteine] In 1884 German chemist Eugen Baumann found that reduction of cystine with zinc gave monomer, which he named "cysteïne".
[src:cysteine/cysteine] The easy redox interconversion of cysteine and cystine has "provided more puzzles to protein chemists than any of the other amino acids.
